# No Duplication

## Scope

Applies to all production source code (`src/`, `backend/`, or equivalent). Test code is explicitly excluded — tests may repeat setup for clarity. Data files and migration scripts are out of scope.

## Rule

Before writing any new function, class, constant, or configuration value: **search the codebase for an existing implementation first.**

If an equivalent already exists: use it, extend it, or move it to a shared location. Never create a second copy.

Cross-module duplication is worse than intra-module duplication. A shared helper module is always preferred over copy-paste across two separate modules.

### Mandatory Pre-Write Checklist

Before implementing anything, answer these questions:

1. **Does this function already exist?**
   ```bash
   grep -rn "function <functionName>\|const <functionName>" src/
   ```
   If found: import and reuse. Do not rewrite.

2. **Does this constant / path / default already exist?**
   Check the central config class (e.g., `AppSettings`, `Settings`) first.
   Check shared model files for reusable interface/type definitions.
   If found: import from there. Do not redefine locally.

3. **Does this utility already exist in a private helper?**
   Private helpers (unexported, module-local) in one module must **not** be imported by other modules. If two modules need the same helper, move it to the appropriate shared location and export it from there.

### Refactoring Obligation

If you discover an existing duplicate while working on a task:

1. Flag it explicitly: `⚠️ DUPLICATION DETECTED: <location A> and <location B>`
2. Consolidate before adding new code — do not leave the duplicate in place
3. Update all call sites
4. Run the test suite to verify nothing broke

---

## Rationale

Duplication multiplies the surface for bugs: when a bug exists in copied logic, it must be fixed in every copy — and one copy is always missed. It increases the cost of every future change, since intent is spread across locations. It obscures ownership: two implementations of the same concept create ambiguity about which is authoritative.

The pre-write checklist is the primary enforcement mechanism. It costs thirty seconds and prevents hours of future debugging.

---

## Hotspot Table

These patterns have historically produced duplicates across projects. Be especially vigilant when working in these areas. Before adding code in any of these categories, grep for an existing implementation first.

| Category | Canonical location (per project) | Do NOT redefine in | Discovered in |
|----------|----------------------------------|-------------------|---------------|
| Storage adapter read/write (file, DB, CSV) | Dedicated repository/adapter module | CLI commands, routers, schedulers | Initial audit |
| Dependency wiring / container setup | Central DI container or `index.ts` entry point | Individual business modules | Initial audit |
| Runtime config & defaults | Central settings class (`AppSettings` or equivalent) | Individual modules | Initial audit |
| Shared domain model instantiation | Injected via constructor | Do not instantiate inline in callers | Initial audit |
| External service model name / version string | Central config | Do not hardcode in call sites | Initial audit |
| Domain-specific extractors (field extraction logic) | Dedicated extractor module | Do not copy into new scrapers or stages | Initial audit |
| Follow-up / queue read logic | Dedicated scheduler module | Routers / handlers (call the module, don't re-implement) | Sprint P35 |
| Schema / data validation logic | Dedicated validator module | Scripts, routers (import only) | Sprint P36 |
| Stage/step handoff in multi-step processing | Pipeline orchestrator | Individual stage modules | Initial audit |
| HTTP client wrapper | Shared HTTP client adapter | Every module that needs HTTP | Initial audit |

